1 Introduction
Freight demand forecasting is of paramount importance to many companies. More than $13 trillion worth of commodities are sent yearly over the United Statesâ€™ freight transportation system. In order to meet the demandâ€™s requirements, appropriate forecasting must be held. It, however, remains rather complex (Doustmohammadi et al., 2016).
Over the past few decades, the demand for freight transportation services has been steadily increasing due to the abundance of international trade. Bottlenecks have highlighted the inefficiency and overall weak points in the system which need improvement to face everincreasing demand. It concerns public and private instances over all means of freight transport (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016).
Freight demand literature has been less abundant than passenger demand although freight participates heavily in traffic congestion, ambient noise and pollution (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011). The modelling of freight transport is more intricate than the modelling of passenger transport. It gathers many more actors and includes specificities depending on the type of commodities being transported.
Emerging countries whose economy relies mainly on exports cannot neglect freight demand optimization. The rail and road compromise requires reflection further than the cost perspective: delay or early arrivals influence storage, manufacturing and downstream sales (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
Transport problems are the same as in the past (congestion, accidents, pollution, costs, etc.). We have learned a lot from times of weak transportation planning. The 21st century has however brought new problems such as fast urbanization, high demand for public transport, scarcity of resources (capital, data and skilled personnel) â€¦ The number of cars and commercial vehicles in use worldwide has increased by more than 38% from 2006 to 2015 (Statista, 2016). Hence the urge to design and plan operations to counter these problems has increased also (HolguÃ­nVeras et al., 2016).
1

In order to acknowledge, analyze and improve this situation, different tools were developed to aid decision-making in the transport literature. As in most research topics related to economic sciences, the transport models confront the supply to the demand. The transport demand is commonly defined as the quantities to transport from each origin to each destination. Therefore, the transport demand is frequently represented in origin-destination matrices. These matrices assign quantities to each pair of origin-destination. Additional frameworks are required to obtain more information on the whereabouts of these quantities. Hence allocation models assign one, or several paths, to the quantities transported for each pair of origin-destination. This allows to observe the flows on a given network. The transport supply is defined as the combination of the services transporters offer, the infrastructure available, the relevant laws and policies, the modes available and miscellaneous transporter characteristics. The goal of this master thesis is to provide an overview of the freight demand forecast models. The first part of this paper will be a literature review of the existing theoretical models to predict freight demand. After a brief explanation of the basic concepts of transport planning, we will examine the classic four-stage transport model as a point of reference and address its limitations. Next, we will provide an introduction to multi-agent systems and review the methods to model freight generation and distribution. The final part of the paper will focus on the review, analysis and comparison of practical models, namely the PLANET model, the TRANS-TOOLS model (which used the ETISplus project database), the FAME model and the ITSAM.
2

2 Literature review
2.1 Freight demand characteristics
Freight transportation refers to the five basic modes of transportation: highway, rail, water, air and pipelines (Doustmohammadi et al., 2016).
The key influencers on the movement of goods are: - The shipper: requires the movement of goods to be delivered to a consignee. He will also choose the forwarder based on reliability, price and quality factors. - The freight forwarder: organizes the shipping process (which mode, at what time, etc.) - The carrier: responsible for the transportation (provides vans, lorries, trains) - The driver: guides the vehicle
There are, of course, more actors, such as insurance companies, the state and officials (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
An important aspect of the transport demand is that it is derived. The demand for transport is not an end goal, the transport is a way to satisfy one or several needs. We first need to understand when, where and how the demand occurs in order to obtain plausible forecasts (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
Time and space are capital elements in demand forecasting. A misinterpretation of where the demand stands greatly impacts the supply and demand equilibrium. Plus, deliveries can be highly inefficient at certain hours of the day. The time element of the demand is dynamic; peak hours, flexible working hours and work shifts must be considered. The planning gets even more intricate when trips are gathered in Tour or Trip Chains (set of linked trips).
Often times, infrastructure and the vehicles are not owned by the same company. The infrastructure takes a lot of combined effort and planning to be changed. Major transport tracks can take from 5 to 15 years to be modified. Therefore, some of them are intricate to change: one cannot add a third of a train station or half a runway to respond to a slight demand raise (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
3

Transportation agencies know very little on the whereabouts of trucks and cargoes; they mostly account for the deliveries. They only have an idea of the network truck traffic and the land use patterns, but they know very little of freight flows. Thus, no agent involved in the freight has enough information to describe the whole network, which causes inefficiency.
On the one hand, theoretically sound models guarantee stable results, consistency, give confidence in the forecasts, help to understand the context and the relevant variables.
On the other hand, practitioners donâ€™t want to use theoretically sound models just to satisfy their academic colleagues. Plus, they are often quite complex, they require scarce data, they cannot always offer an appropriate level of detail and they donâ€™t often offer a lot of flexibility.
The choice between the two depends on the context, and the level of detail required. Balance should be found between theory and expedience in every decision taken (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
2.2 Factors affecting freight movement
The factors affecting freight movement are: - Location factors: the location of all inputs and the place where the commodity is sold or consumed will greatly influence the amount of Freight movement. - The variety of products needed to assemble the freight: the more specific pieces required, the more intermediate transportation. - Physical factors: the way commodities must be transported (in cold/warm cargoes, in bulk, packaged, with high securityâ€¦) - Operational factors: the size of the firm, its geographical dispersion. - Geographical factors: where the customers are, how dispersed they are. - Dynamic factors: seasonalities, - Pricing factors: as opposed to passenger demand, prices are generally not published because of bargaining power and negotiation (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
4

2.3 Freight/Non-Freight Intensive Sectors
There is an overall tendency for humans to pay attention to events of a greater size, whereas repeated events of a smaller size pass unnoticed. For example, distribution centers with large trucks that deliver large quantities are easily detected, but few people would suspect the food and retail sector in a big city generates several times more traffic than most ports and distribution centers (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016).
It is therefore useful to classify the industry sectors into two groups: 1. Freight Intensive Sectors (FIS), for which â€œconsumption and production of cargoes are central to the activity performed by the establishmentâ€ (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 14). 2. Non-Freight Intensive Sectors (non-FIS), for which â€œproduction and consumption of cargoes are of secondary importanceâ€ (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 14).
Metropolitan areas are of paramount importance. Itâ€™s also important to note that deliveries to urban areas using delivery vans and small trucks typically represent 80% to 90% of total freight traffic. These are short trips with a high frequency to counter the fact that urban areas have little storage room. This mode of freight transportation is also more adequate to increasingly important â€œreverse logisticsâ€ of returns and exchanges (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016).
2.4 Four layers of decisions and activities
Freight movements can be seen as the result of four layers of decisions and activities. 1 â€“ Decisions on production: destination, type of product, volume and trade relationships (who produces what, in what quantities and for what intermediate or final consumer) 2 â€“ Logistics: decisions on the use and location of inventories and supply chain management 3 â€“ Choice of transport modes (including multimodal) 4 â€“ Transport route followed, more complex for multimodal
The attention allocated to each layer depends on the scope and geography of the study.
5

To sum up, the research has been less significant in freight modeling than passenger modeling for the following reasons:
- Many aspects of freight demand make it harder to model than passenger movements. - Urban congestion is mainly caused by people movement. - The movement of freight involves more actors: shippers, receivers, transporters, storage
facilitators, manufacturersâ€¦ The most classical approach to the problem is to adopt the conventional four-stage demand model to the case of commodities (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
2.5 The Classic Four-Stage Transport Model
This model is built around the concepts of zones and networks. The geographical area or establishment group studied is seen as a zone. The model is represented in Figure 1. It is divided in four stages (or four steps): - Trip Generation: Firstly, data is assessed to determine the number of trips entering and leaving the studied zone. - Distribution: Secondly, the destination of these trips is recorded in an Origin-Destination matrix. - Modal Split: Next, the trips are characterized depending on their transportation mode. - Assignment: Finally, the last step assigns the trips to their corresponding networks: private or public transport.
6

Figure 1: The classic four-stage transport model
This four-stage transport model isnâ€™t the only option, but it is known as a solid point of reference.
In the case of interurban movements, stochastic assignment models are often used. However, each vehicle type can have specific modeling drawbacks.
Vans might not be sensitive to the slopes of routes whereas lorries are. Vehicles carrying perishable goods should be prioritized against those carrying sand or other non-perishable goods. The use of multi-class assignment methods may then be warranted to cope with this variety of cost concepts. Lorry drivers often prefer to drive at night to avoid traffic jams, but they are sometimes constrained to drive at rush hours due to short delivery times.
The use of the shortest path algorithm is likely to require incremental path searches. The algorithm should somehow take into consideration different train types (slow local trains, faster direct trains) and contain realistic penalties for delaying operations at transfer locations (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
7

2.5.1 First Stage: Trip Generation
The trip generation stage predicts the number of trips generated and attracted to each zone (Mathew & Krishna Rao, 2007).
The Freight and Service Activity (FSA) can be divided into two processes: the process of attraction (the flow that arrives to perform an activity) and the process of production (the flow that leaves the establishment to perform activity elsewhere). Hence the following metrics can be divided into attraction and production:
Freight Generation (FG): the amount of cargo generated by an establishment usually calculated by weight/day (tons/day). It is the â€œeconomic activity performed at a business establishment by which input materials are processed and transformed generating an output that, in most cases, is transported elsewhere for further processing, storage, distribution, or consumptionâ€ (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 2). It is the sum of:
- Freight Attraction (FA): amount of cargo brought to the establishment to be processed, stored or sold.
- Freight Production (FP): amount of cargo sent out. Establishments that sell the final product to the customer have an FP=0, if an establishment conducts intermediate processing, FP>0.
Freight Trip Generation (FTG): the number of freight generated trips by an establishment. Hence any flow creates two trips: inbound and outbound. FTG is defined as â€œthe result of the logistics decisions concerning how best to transport the FG in terms of shipment size, frequency of deliveries, and vehicle/mode usedâ€ (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 2). It is the sum of:
- Freight Trip Attraction (FTA): number of trips arriving to the establishment. - Freight Trip Production (FTP): number of trips departing from the establishment.
Establishments that donâ€™t have FP will generate no FTP. FTG is not necessarily proportional to the size of the company. The shipper can change the shipment size without affecting the number of trips.
The models using FG/FTG work best if the internal economic occupation is as homogeneous as possible. Industrial classification systems, such as the Standard Industrial Code (SIC) can be used to make classifications as homogeneous as possible.
8

HolguÃ­n-Veras et al. (2016) also stressed that FTG and FG should be seen as separate. â€œThe amount and nature of the incoming and outgoing Freight Generation depends on the type of business, and its size. In contrast, the FTG depends on the corresponding shipment sizes and the ability of the carriers to consolidate their shipmentsâ€ (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 13).
The economic nature1 of the models reveals the link between FG and FTG: FG is the output of an economic process, FTG is the output of logistic decisions on the size and frequency of the shipments. But there is no one-to-one relationship between both: increasing shipment size could lower the number of trips without affecting the number of commodities (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016).
2.5.1.1 Home-Based and Non-Home-Based Trips
Trips are also often classified by their source and purpose. In home-based (HB) trips, the home of the trip initiator is either the origin or the destination of the trip. Non-home-based (NHB) trips are journeys that donâ€™t involve the home of the initiator. NHB amount to only 15 to 20% of all trips.
â€œTrip Production is the home end of an HB trip or the origin of an NHB trip. Trip Attraction is the non-home end of an HB trip or the destination of an NHB trip.â€ This is explained in Figure 2 (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011, p. 140).
Figure 2: Trip productions and attractions
(OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011)
1 Reminder: the amount of cargo produced and consumed are bound to economic transactions
9

Freight trip productions and attractions only amount to 20% of all the trips, yet they can be of significant importance to traffic congestion.
Important variables include: - number of employees, - number of sales, - roofed area of the firm, - total area of the firm.
2.5.1.2 Production-Consumption Link and the Importance of Service
The concept of a Production-Consumption (PC) link is the transaction that binds a producer to its customer. There can be simple supply chains with few PC links, or very complex ones with numerous of PC links corresponding to the stages of the production process. PC links have great importance in the understanding of freight demand. Transportation flows materialize into freight traffic. Hence, the analysis of Freight Trip Generation must consider:
1. Production sites and shippers 2. Intermediate processing points 3. Intermediate and end consumer sites
Service should not be overlooked: â€œAs an example (â€¦) the 10,000 restaurants and bars in Manhattan, New York, produce more truck traffic than do the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey terminals combined.â€ (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 10)
Service trips are generated by technicians, service providers, who visit an establishment to perform various services. Hence, services greatly contribute to congestion. This should ideally be considered in the making of a freight demand forecast model.
10

2.5.1.3 Trip Generation Modeling
Trip generation models are often developed using regression analysis. Generally, the functional form will be a multiple linear regression model whose equation resembles the following:
y = a0 + (a1 x1) + (a2 x2) + (a3 x3) + â€¦ + (an xn) + e
Equation 1
In case of a one-variable model, the equation would be: y = a0 + (a1 x1) + e
Equation 2
Where y = dependent variableâ€¨ xi = independent variable (i = 1, 2, 3â€¦n)â€¨ a0 = constant termâ€¨ ai = coefficient of independent variables (i = 1, 2, 3â€¦n)â€¨ e = error termâ€¨ n = number of independent variables (Modi et al., 2011)
The category analysis (or cross classification analysis) is a frequent alternative to regression methods. It is commonly used to determine the number of trips generated using criteria such as household groups, the range of income and car ownership. It is, however, mostly relevant for passenger trip generation. Therefore, it will not be detailed in this paper. The growth factor model (developed further, in section 2.5.2.1) can also be applied to trip generation. (Sarkar et al., 2017).
2.5.2 Second Stage: Trip Distribution
In order to obtain a better representation of trips, they can be represented as â€œtrip matrixâ€ or â€œtrip tablesâ€. This consists in storing trips depending on their origin and destination within a period. Another way to represent trip patterns is by assessing the factors that generate and attract trips.
11

These matrices are two-dimensional array of cells (Table 1), rows represent origins, columns are the destinations. The diagonal represents intro-zonal trips.
Table 1: A general form of a two-dimensional trip matrix
Tij is the number of trips between origin i and destination j. Origin-Destination (O-D) matrices can be further disaggregated, for instance, by transportation modes and by commodity type. The sum of the trips in a row/column should be equal to the number of trips produced from/attracted to that zone (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
