2.5.2.1 Trip Distribution Modeling

Linear Programming

A first approach to freight distribution modelling is Linear Programming (LP), which tries to minimize haulage costs subject to supply and demand constraints.

Subject to

ğ‘€ğ‘–ğ‘›ğ‘–ğ‘šğ‘–ğ‘§ğ‘’ ğ‘ = ğ‘‡"#ğ¶"#
"#
Equation 3

ğ‘‡"# = ğ·#
"
ğ‘‡"# = ğ‘‚"
#

Where ğ‘‡"# are tons of the product moved from i to j; ğ¶"# are generalized transport costs per ton of products between zones i and j; ğ‘‚"0, ğ·#0 are supply and demand at zone i (or j) (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011, p.467).

The LP approach gives more realistic results when: - the industry contains few firms;â€¨ - it deals with low-value goods and high transportation costs;â€¨ - there are few demand points (buyers)

LP gives satisfying results of the behavior of a single client or industrial firm, but it wonâ€™t truthfully represent aggregate behavior for various commodities (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).

Growth factor models
Growth factor models can be used to simply determine a future number of journeys. They are based on the assumption that future transport pattern can be forecasted simply by taking the current patterns and multiplying them by a growth factor.
13

The Uniform Growth Factor model is a crude and very simplistic method. It should only be used if the only information available is a general fluctuation rate on studied zones.

Its basic equation is:

Tij =F * tij
Equation 4

Where Tij = future number of trips from zone i to zone j; tij = current number of trips from zone i to zone j; F = The uniform growth factor.

This model can be useful for short-term planning but the main drawback is that the same growth factor will be used on every zone. Slightly improved versions of this model are the Average Growth Factor model and the Fratar model. They take into account multiple growth factors, but can still cause major inaccuracies (Modi et al., 2011).

The Doubly Constrained Growth Factor model performs better than the ones quoted above but requires more data. It takes two sets of growth factors for each zone studied: one for the trips entering the zone, and one for the trips leaving the zone (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).

The Gravity Model

The gravity model is linked to Newtonâ€™s gravitational law. It reveals macroscopic relationships between zones. â€œThe gravity model assumes that the trips produced at an origin and attracted to a destination are directly proportional to the total trip productions at the origin and the total attractions at the destination.â€ (University of Idaho, n.d., p.1)

The model considers the likeliness of a trip to be made according to its duration, distance (University of Idaho, n.d., p.1) and supply and demand constraints (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011). This likeliness lies in the calibration parameters Î²k (also known as the friction factor). The calibration of the model is a prerequisite step to use the model for demand forecasts.

14

The Gravity Modelâ€™s functional form applied to freight forecast is:
ğ‘‡"0# = ğ´0" ğµ#0ğ‘‚"0ğ·#0exp (âˆ’ğ›½0ğ¶"0#)
Equation 5
Where k is a commodity type index, ğ‘‡"0# are tons of product k moved from i to j; Ak, Bk are balancing factors with their usual interpretation; ğ‘‚"0, ğ·#0 are supply and demand for product k at zone i (or j); Î²k are calibration parameters, one per product k; ğ¶"0# are generalized transport costs per ton of product k between zones i and j. (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011, p.466).
A generalized cost function can be drawn out from that: (omitting the suffix k for simplicity) ğ¶"# = ğ‘“"# + ğ‘Cğ‘ "# + ğ‘Eğœğ‘ "# + ğ‘Gğ‘¤"# + ğ‘Iğ‘"#
Equation 6
where fij is the out-of-pocket charge for using a service from i to j; sij is a door-to-door travel time between i and j; Ïƒ sij is the variability of travel time s; wij is the waiting time or delay from requests for service to actual delivery â€“ it may be a
long time for maritime transport for example, pij is the probability of loss or damage to goods in transit. (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011,
p. 467)
All these factors depend on the mode used and the commodity transported. The constants ğ‘K are at least proportional to the value of the goods. For instance, in case of loss, the cost will likely be more than the goodâ€™s value, due to penalties for delays in delivery.
In general terms, it is important to consider the contribution of transport costs to the final cost of a commodity. For example, in the case of wheat, coal, cement and bricks, transport costs are a main element in their final price; however, in the case of convenience foods, consumer goods, chocolates or electronics, transport costs have a low (direct) contribution to price (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
15

The gravity model is the most flexible and exhaustive model presented in this section.
The relationship between LP and gravity models has been explored by Evans (1973). When Î² approaches 0, (in equation 5) transport costs will tend to negligible; while a very large value for Î² generates a solution closer to that of an LP model. Hence, the gravity model can engulf the LP model and give accurate results for a wide range of commodities, regardless of the importance of the costs in transportation.
2.5.3 Third Stage: Modal choice
The aim of this stage is to determine the separation between transport modes. It is considered one of the most important stages of the four-stage model. It enables the development of policies to regulate the traffic and road congestion. Mode choice greatly affects efficiency.
The freight mode choice is made by the shipper who decides which mode or combination of modes should be used to send its goods. Each mode has a set of benefits compared to the others, the key is to compare their costs to the efficiency researched (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
Inventory management can have a great impact on the modal choice. Low inventories imply relying strongly on transportation. The mode choice has to address many concerns to deliver reliable, flexible, time-effective and cost-effective services (CUTR, n.d.)
A very common mode choice modelling method is the Multinomial Logit (MNL) formulation (based on generalized costs). The main drawback is that the formulation is built upon the generalized costs solely, which likely creates approximate results (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
The following table gathers the variables explaining mode choice for freight demand forecasting. They were separated in four categories, as suggested by the Center for Urban Transportation Research at theâ€¨University of South Florida (CUTR, n.d.). The factors were extracted from the papers of Cook et al. (1999), Cullinane & Toy (2000) and Jiang et al. (1999).
16

