According to the Center for Urban Transportation Research at theâ€¨University of South Florida (n.d.), the factors in Table 2 hold the highest potential for influence through policy intervention.

However, their influence might vary upon different criteria. As an example, the type of commodity can be one of the main concerns as it can influence the importance of other factors. â€œPrice is the most important factor for coal, while transit time is the most important factor for food grainsâ€ (CUTR, n.d., p.15).

17

Cook et al. (1999) also stated that policy interventions can shift the balance among these factors. For sake of clarity, Cullinane & Toy (2000)â€™s analysis ranked the five most important factors as the following:
1. Cost/Price/Rate, Speed 2. Transit time 3. Reliability 4. Characteristics of the goods 5. Service (unspecified).
A table was developed by the Center for Urban Transportation Research at the University of South Florida to identify at which point in time the factors from Table 2 come into play. This table is covered in Appendix 3.
2.5.4 Limits of the Four-Stage Model
The four-stage model was initially developed for passenger transport. Several authors (such as Shankar, Pendyala and Dâ€™Este) acknowledged that the structure can be applied to freight transport as well. However, the models within of these four stages can be much more diverse than those for passenger transport. Indeed, there are many more decision makers (shippers, carriers, intermediatesâ€¦) and the diversity of the type items represents different and more numerous requirements than for passenger transport (de Jong et al, 2004).
Aside from these four stages, transformation modules are often required (to convert physical flows into tons, and tons into vehicle units, for instance). They are of paramount importance because the converted variables may impact the final predictions greatly. Transformation modules are influenced by decisions on shipment size and frequency, returns and vehicle utilization rates. These decisions could be modelled explicitly in additional logistic modules (for instance, in the FAME model, analyzed further in this paper) or the conversion rates could be fixed in the assumptions of the model.
18

Inaccuracies could also be engendered for the following reasons: â€¢ The zonesâ€™ characteristics and compositions are assumed constant throughout the forecast horizon. The development of the transport modes isnâ€™t considered either. For instance, the introduction of new trains on the network, which would slightly increase delays and congestion, would have no influence on the frequency of trips (de Jong et al, 2004).
â€¢ For trip distribution, the average travel time is assumed to remain the same throughout any day and in the future. There is no consideration of peak/off-peak hours in the original four-stage model. The utility function for the modal choice is also considered constant no matter what time of the day/day of the week it is.
â€¢ Finally, the model always represents the average behavior of a group of actors. Analyzing the network in zones only does not consider the shipper/travelerâ€™s value of time and modal preferences. The model cannot forecast the behavior of an individual actor accurately (Mladenovic, 2014).
2.6 Activity-Based Models and Multi-Agent Systems
Most of the demand generation models, as shown by OrtÃºzar & Willumsen (2011), have the drawback of being trip-based (which means they assume the transport demand as a sum of independent and isolated trips) and have no regard to the time at which the trips are made. Both criteria are of paramount importance: trips are interconnected in the supply chain and sending truck off-peak hours can drastically improve the journey performance.
Consequently, activity-based models should be emphasized. They consider time, space, the different actors involved in the transport and the type of activity. They emphasis the generation of activity/logistic chains. These models were developed much later than the trip based models (HÃ¤gerstrand, 1970; Chapin, 1974; Fried, et al., 1977; Jones, et al., 1983) (Piotte, 2013).
In his report, Ferber (1995) explains the intricacies of the methodology of the multi-agent systems.
19

The multi-agent system paradigm was designed to simulate the behavior and interactions between different actors of a system according to their needs and objectives. A multi-agent system is a computerized system in which actors are represented as autonomous virtual entities called agents. This concept can approach activity-based problems and reflect the demand more realistically than simple trip-based models. The initiator of multi-agent systems lets agents meticulously modeled interact to further analyze the macroscopic results.
According to Ferber (1995), physical or virtual entities: - are able to act in an environment, - are able to communicate directly with other agents, - are powered by individual objectives or a satisfaction/survival function that they try to optimize, - possess their own resources, - are able to perceive their environment (to a limited extent), - dispose of a limited representation of the environment, - possess skills and provide services, - can potentially reproduce, - behave to satisfy its objectives, taking into account resources and skills available, and according to their perception, representations and interactions.
He defines a multi-agent system as a system composed of: - an environment, a space that generally hosts a metric, - a set of objects, whose position is recorded. These objects are passive, which means they can be perceived, created, destroyed and modified by agents, - a set of agents, - a set of relationships, joining objects and agents altogether, - a set of operations allowing agents to perceive, create, destroy and modify objects, - operators that represent the application of these operations and the reaction to the world.
20

Multi-agent systems are used in various sectors such as urban design (Valbuena et al., 2010), ecology (Saqalli et al., 2010), social sciences (Pavon et al., 2008) and studies of epidemic propagation. Davidson, et al. (2005) conducted a specific inquiry on the use of multi-agent systems in the transport field. The paper gathers and criticizes the results of existing methods and models (Piotte, 2013). One of the main difficulties of the multi-agent systems is the validation of the simulation. Louie & Carley (2008) suggested solutions to validate such models. They also emphasis the fact that multi-agent models require a significant amount of desegregate data. Gathering every piece of data necessary is often impossible. Hence, Louie & Carley (2008)â€™s paper tries to advice on data representativeness and exhaustiveness. It also explains the concept of macroscopic validation which consists in analyzing the coherence of the whole multi-agent system and comparing the system results with data drawn from the real world. Multi-agent systems are able to simulate freight transport generation and incorporate time series. Piotteâ€™s doctoral thesis (2013) covers this intricate topic and applies it to the Walloon region in Belgium.
21

3 Classifying Freight Demand Models
Different models are used to effectively reflect the demand in the short run and in the long run. As of 2016, the freight demand forecasting models are not as developed and accurate compared to passenger transportation forecasting. One of the main issues is that more parties are involved in freight transportation. The abundance of variables also explains the complexity to obtain accurate and generalizable results (Doustmohammadi et al., 2016).
The variables of a chosen model should correctly measure the intensity of freight and service activity. In other words, the variables should somehow be correlated to the economic growth (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016).
3.1 Aggregate vs. Disaggregate Data
Aggregate data is sometimes the only type of data available. It is only relevant to use aggregate data when its components are assumed endogenous. Aggregate freight demand models represent a vast majority of the freight demand models. However, aggregate models can be inaccurate, costly and inflexible.
Disaggregate approaches can be more accurate but require higher statistical and econometric skills.
[Disaggregate] models are very efficient because they (1) require smaller samples than their aggregate counterparts (2) establish a direct connection between the attributes of the establishment and the measure of FSA [Freight Service Activity] that is being estimated, and (3) could be aggregated to any level of geography (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016, p. 20).
However, this type of approach has found limited application. The main reasons for this are: - the limited understanding of all the elements involved in developing these utility functions and - the very demanding data-collection efforts required to estimate this type of model.
Data collection for disaggregate approaches suffers from confidentiality and reliability problems.
22

Yet there is no definitive approach, aggregate and disaggregate models both have their pros and cons. Even collecting data for aggregate modelling represents a much greater effort than that for passenger movements: great dispersion of firms, important daily and seasonal variations, and so on (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011).
3.2 Attributes Influencing Freight Trip Generation
An intuitive factor that influences the amount of freight generated is the size of the business (the larger the business, the larger the freight generation). Nonetheless, freight trip generation relies upon many more factors such as inventories, logistic costs and the number of establishments. Table 3, provided by the National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (2012), lists factors that influence freight trip generation. These factors will be used to analyze and compare the practical models in section 4.5 of this paper. The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine also provided a list of important factors to take under consideration to analyze or develop freight modeling techniques. These are listed in Table 4.
23

Table 3: Summary of findings concerning attributes influencing freight trip generation
(National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, 2012)
24

Table 4: Review factors for freight modeling techniques
(National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, 2012)
3.2.1 Example of attribute: linking the forecasts to employment
This section aims to show the way to use an attribute of Table 3 to forecast freight demand.
3.2.1.1 Why the employment
The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (2012) defined two sets of models:
- the first set uses a traditional independent set of variables such as employment, - the second set uses spatial variables such as proximity to similar businesses. Although the use of spatial proxies leads to better results, the data remains quite out of reach for most analysts. With employment data being publicly available, it is often used as the only independent variable. Employment statistics are periodically released. Furthermore, it gives a fair representation of the economy (National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine, 2012).
25

