3.3 History of model classifications
Several classifications of freight demand forecast models have been made over the past 35 years. The major part of the literature focuses on modal choice or differentiating aggregate and disaggregate models. Winston (1985) opposed aggregate and disaggregate models based on the nature of the data used.
Oum (1989) furthered this opposition stating that the model choice depended on the study purpose and the availability of data. He also came to the conclusion that this opposition wasnâ€™t a good classification for freight demand forecast models, because long-term freight demand forecast models are mostly aggregate models.
Some papers suggest other considerations than modal choice: Harker (1987) distinguishes econometric models and network balance models. The econometric models he referred to are in fact the aggregate and disaggregate models that have the end goal of modal choice. The network balance models combine route choice and modal choice.
28

Next, Regan and Garrido (2002) distinguished models according to their geographical spread (international transport, inter-urban transport, transport within a city...).
3.4 The most recent classification system: Freight Demand Forecasting in Class
In 2008, the National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP, 2008) listed 5 traditional approaches applied in the United States, which are classified from class A to E. Here is a brief explanation of each class:
â€¢ Class A, the Direct facility flow factoring method, estimates growth in truck transport and applies it to truck traffic volumes. It, however, implies many assumptions and is infrequently applicable.
â€¢ Class B, the O-D factoring method, is the same as Class A, except the growth is applied in the Origin-Destination table of the truck transport. Yet, data acquisition availability for this class represents an important problem for the implementation.
â€¢ Class C, the Truck model, aggregates truck trips per zone, distinguishing trips between or into internal and external geographical zones. The main drawback is that the analysis is limited to the freight truck mode, these models are unable to analyze shifts between modes.
â€¢ Class D, the Four-stage commodity model, is a commodity-based version of class C. It uses forecasts of commodities and applies them to the daily trips. It supports multiple transport modes. It allows to conduct impact analyses, but they do not explain the interaction between industries.
â€¢ Class E, the Economic activity model, gathers relationships between two relevant models in order to develop a more robust model (for instance, by fusing an economic/land model with a freight demand forecast model). Nonetheless, they do not take into account the performance of transportation facilities (Doustmohammadi et al., 2016).
However, â€œNo model in class A to E alone is capable of addressing all freight policy and analytical needs. Also, the models pay little attention to truck types, trip patterns, trip lengths, or comparisons with truck counts (which are very difficult to obtain).â€ (Doustmohammadi et al., 2016, p. 20).
29

Two classifications should be added to these five traditional ones, according to Doustmohammadi et al. (2016). Classes F and G go further and refer to advanced freight demand forecasting models facing current or up-coming problems.
â€¢ Class F, the Logistics Chain Models, emerged from the need for sensitivity in the economics of commodities.
â€¢ Class G, the Vehicle Touring Models, tries to truthfully represent trucks motion for impact assessment.
These two models have the drawbacks that the data isnâ€™t readily available and that the models are quite costly and hard to put into practice. Table 6 shows the advantages and disadvantages of using methods of each class.
Table 6: Class advantages and disadvantages
(Doustmohammadi et al., 2016) Overall, the published literature on the application of tour-based models (Class G) suggests that such models are more realistic than traditional freight demand forecasting models and best suited for impact assessment and vehicle-based policy studies, such as pricing strategies and restricted lanes (Doustmohammadi et al., 2016).
30

Table 7 shows the relationship between each class and its inputs/outputs. It can be very useful to observe which type of model to reference depending on the available data.
Table 7: Freight model characteristics by Input/output
(Doustmohammadi et al., 2016) These last two tables will be helpful to classify and compare the real-world models analyzed in the next part of this paper.
31

4 Real-world models
This section deals with macro-models that have been developed by public entities to forecast freight demand in different zones of the world. They all use concepts and frameworks explained in sections 2 and 3 to forecast freight demand in Belgium, Europe, the United States and western Asia in practice.
4.1 PLANET Model
4.1.1 Description of the model
The PLANET model is a long-run model oriented towards transport in Belgium. It was developed by the Federal Planning Bureau in collaboration with the SPF Mobility and Transport. The bureau comes up with long run outlooks on the freight and passenger demand in Belgium every three years. The model also aims to:
- develop long run perspectives on the freight and passenger demand in Belgium, - evaluate the effects of transport policies, pollution costs and congestion costs on the
actual transport activity, - carry out profit analysis of these transport policies.
The PLANET model is composed of seven interconnected modules: 1. The Macro module 2. The Transport Generation module 3. The Trip Distribution module 4. The Modal and Time Choice module 5. The Vehicle Stock module 6. The Welfare module 7. The Policy module
These 7 interconnected modules are illustrated in Figure 4, their relationships will be explained further in the next pages (Vandresse, 2016)
32

Macro

TRANSPORT: -Transport Generation
-Trip Distribution -Modal and Time Choice
-Vehicle stock

Welfare

Policies

(Vandresse, 2016)

Figure 4: Modules of the PLANET model

The Macro module sets macroeconomic projections at the level of the â€œarrondissementsâ€ (NUTS33 zones) of Belgium. The results from the Macro module are considered as exogenous to the rest of the model. Only the impact of the economic and demographic variables is examined.

The Policy module outlines the transport policies used in usual and alternative scenarios. These consist in transport instruments (such as fuel taxes, vehicle purchase taxes or road pricing) but also encompass more general instruments such as labor taxation.

The part of PLANET focused on transport gathers four modules: â€¢ The Transport Generation module determines the number of journeys between home and workplace for each zone, the number of other passenger trips and the total tons of freight transported nationally and internationally.

3 NUTS3 stands for the third level of the Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics. It is a territorial division to ease comparison between countries or regions. The level depends on the number of inhabitants of the region. (Eurostat, 2017)
33

â€¢ The results of the Transport Generation module are provided to the Trip Distribution module which determines the number of trips taking place between each of the zones.
â€¢ Next, the Modal and Time Choice module aligns the modes by which the trips are made and the timeframe in the case of road transport (peak hours or off-peak hours). The choice of mode and time period depends on the costs and length of the different options. Travel time for the road modes is determined by means of the speed-flow function that links the average speed of transport modes to the traffic flow.
â€¢ The road transport demand obtained from that function is used as an input for the Vehicle Stock module. This module reveals the composition of the stock of vehicles registered in Belgium according to their size, the current EURO norm, and the cubic capacity and type of their engine. The Modal and Time Choice and Vehicle Stock modules disclose information on environmental costs of transports and public revenues generated from transports.
In some cases, results for a given year (t) determine the transport demand for the following year (t+1). Hence, the transport demand can depend on the average generalized cost of the transport flux of the previous year. Furthermore, the generalized cost of transport on a given year influences the following yearâ€™s trip distribution. Finally, the Vehicle Stock has an impact on the following yearâ€™s road transport costs. This is illustrated in Figure 5.
Figure 5: Links between transport modules in PLANET
(Vandresse, 2016)
34

The Welfare module calculates the effects of transport policies on welfare. The module takes into account effects on consumers, producers, public authorities and the environment.
4.1.2 Methodology
4.1.2.1 Calibration of the model
The exogenous parameters of the model are determined in the calibration step in order to better simulate the behavior of modal choice. The reference year for calibration is 2008 due to the fact that:
- All the necessary data is available for 2008 (costs, transport statisticsâ€¦). It also follows the introduction of the latest uniform freight classification (NST 2007).
- No particular crisis or biasing events occurred in 2008. Calibrating on an atypical year wouldnâ€™t yield good results. The model, however, takes the economic crisis into account using macroeconomic forecasts conducted in 2011.
Following the introduction of the NST 2007, an origin-destination matrix has been built for the year 2008. The input data came from the Directorate General Statistics and Economic Information (DGSIE) for road and marine transport. The rail data was retrieved from the SNCB.
On a macroeconomic level, three main factors influence transport demand: employment, production and international trade. Hence, the evolution of the gross domestic product, the economic and financial crisis, the geographical spreading of employment and the changes of industry sector are some of the inputs of the PLANET model (Vandresse, 2016).
4.1.2.2 Assumptions
Three categories of costs are considered in the model: - The monetary costs supported by the user (the acquisition and utilization of the vehicle), - The time costs, the monetary value attributed to the journey time, - The environmental costs, even though they often arenâ€™t the first concern of the individual choosing a transport mode.
35

The determination of forecasts of these costs requires several assumptions (considering only freight demand forecasting):
Monetary costs - Motorization doesnâ€™t affect road freight transportation (all trucks and lorries are assumed to run on diesel). But diesel consumption is assumed to reduce over the years thanks to an increase of engine efficiency. Other costs are expected to remain constant. - Regarding rail and marine freight transport, all costs should remain constant, except fuel and electricity costs, which will also benefit from enhanced energy efficiency.
Time costs - The time spent in the vehicle is the only criterion assumed variable over the forecasted period (from 2008 to 2030). - Roads are becoming wider and allow a greater capacity of vehicles, but the number of vehicle continues to increase. Hence, the road lead time is assumed to remain constant over the forecasted period.
Environmental costs - Pollution emissions are bound to decrease over the forecasted period due to legal obligations to vehicle manufacturers to reduce the emissions of their vehicles. - Regarding indirect emission costs, the production of electricity for trains is considered constant over the forecasted period. However, a consistent but moderate increase for hybrid and electric vehicles has been determined. - The fall of nuclear power for alternative energy sources is also assumed. - As the scarcity of fossil fuels increases, the indirect costs for transportation of petrol are predicted to increase. Fossil fuels will be collected farther away from their distribution points, which would require additional transportation (Vandresse, 2016).
36

4.1.2.3 Indicators used for the freight demand forecast
The different indicators are: - The transported tonnage, - The geographical spreading of the transport, - The number of tons-kilometers, - The modal and time choice.
Transported Tonnage The transported tonnage is calculated from the evolution of economic activity (production, import and exports) and the average value of the transport of a ton. The latter depends on the type of freight transported and the distribution of the categories of freight within the transport streams. Marine, air and pipeline transport is determined exogenously. The tonnage for 2008 was determined statistically. For the years 2008 to 2030, the forecasts were made upon the annual growth rate of imports and exports per freight type (using the NST 2007 classification).
Geographical Spreading of the Transport Origin-destination matrices are calculated endogenously to the model. The calculus is made upon a linked model established for each freight type (NST 2007) and is estimated from flows of goods (or freight flows) studied in 2008. The freight flows between geographic areas (â€œarrondissementsâ€ in this case) depend on the generalized cost of transport and the characteristics of the area (population, production, presence of port or airportâ€¦). Public regulations and other commercial barriers are also taken into account.
The Modal and Time Choice Four transport modes were considered: lorries, trucks, trains and barges. Regarding road freight transport, transporters could choose their time period of travel (peak hours or off-peak hours). The modal and time choice is determined from the generalized cost of transport and the freight demand characteristics (for instance, the type of freight) (Vandresse, 2016).
37

4.1.2.4 Alternative Scenarios
This model strongly relies on the assumptions detailed in section 4.1.2.2. It was built around the policies under application in 2008. Yet, government representatives constantly work on strengthening rules against the negative effects of transport. Hence, some alternative scenarios were explored for this model:
- Hybrid and electric cars might develop and sell more than what has been predicted by 2030
- The introduction of stronger taxes on kilometers is likely to be applied to lorries and trucks.
Additional scenarios might occur, but this last part of the report reveals the sensibility of the model and stresses the importance of the assumptions it is built on (Vandresse, 2016).
4.2 TRANS-TOOLS model
The TRANS-TOOLS (TOOLS for TRansport Forecasting ANd Scenario testing) model was funded by the European Commission and DG MOVE (De Jong et al., 2016).
â€œThe TRANS-TOOLS model is the most recent state-of-the-practice transport-oriented 4-steps forecast model available at EU level.â€ (Johansen, 2016, p.1). Its goal is to produce a European transport network model for both passenger and freight. It also deals with intermodal transport, which is a first for European transport network models.
It produces results such as: â€¢ Transport performance (passenger-kilometers, ton-kilometers, vehicle kilometers, etc.) at EU, national and NUTS 4II level, on an annual basis or more detailed,
4 NUTS1: 3 to 7 million inhabitant zones NUTS2: 800 000 to 3 million inhabitant zones NUTS3: 150 000 to 800 000 inhabitant zones
38

â€¢ Modal split (share of demand using road modes, rail, air, etc.) both with reference to passengers and tons and to passenger-kilometers and ton-kilometers, thus also average distance of transport can be assessed,
â€¢ Load on corridors (passengers and freight vehicles) and, therefore, levels of congestion on road infrastructure (TEN-T and main national links), and also, annual averages, and if available, daily peaks (Johansen, 2016, p.1).
The model sorts the flow of goods per commodity type. The freight and logistics model of TRANS-TOOL 3 takes scenarios as input and uses the pivoting approach to generate origindestination matrices.
The TRANS-TOOLS 3 freight model is composed of:
- A trade model to deliver zone-to-zone production-consumption matrices in tons; - Single modal route choice models to generate transport costs and times, and chain route
choice models to calculate overall costs and times for a number of multimodal transport chain types; - A disaggregate logistics model for transport chain choice (encompassing mode choice); - Aggregation to zone-to-zone OD flows (tons); - Chain route choice and network loading (assignment of tonnes); - Pivot-point procedure to pivot predicted OD flow changes on a base OD matrix;â€¨ - Unimodal Assignment of flows onto the networks. (De Jong et al., 2016, p.13)
The specificity of the TRANS-TOOLS sub-models is that they rely on the AggregateDisaggregate-Aggregate (ADA) model. These ADA models have the characteristic of including logistic decisions such as shipment size and transport chains.
Transport flows between NUTS3 zones are covered in the Trans-Tools trade models. They rely on the gravity model explained in section 2.5.2.1.
The main freight model links the demand and supply of transport. The model can thus predict changes due to user input/scenarios regarding the supply and demand.
39

Figure 6 groups the sub-models into the 3 model components: the level of service calculation, the demand response calculation, and the route choice and network loading. The next section will briefly explain how the model is used as a whole.
Figure 6: Main model-groups in the Freight and Logistics Model flow
(De Jong et al., 2016, p.20) 40

4.2.1 Level of Service calculation
â€œThe Level of Service (LoS) is a mechanism used to determine how well a transportation facility is operating from a travelerâ€™s perspectiveâ€ (Thurston Regional Planning Council, 2016)
1 â€“ Single modal route choice models5
The first step of the Level of Service calculation is the use of single modal route choice models. These models calculate level of service (which refers to the time and cost per container or tons) between zones and terminals for road transport, and other modes (rail, inland waterways, sea). This first step considers trucks separately because they can drive directly to the end users, whereas trains and boats require terminals.
The first type of network is the road route. It uses inputs such as length, modelled congested speed, tolls (evaluating time lost at tolls), and time loss at certain border crossings.
The rail route choice sub-models recognize 3 possible combinations of traction; . Diesel the entirety of the journey, â€¨ . Switching of locomotive from diesel to electric or vice versa, â€¨ . Electric the entirety of the journey. â€¨
Diesel is the most expensive method and changing locomotive will result in switching costs (both in time and capital).
Hence, the rail route choice model considers travel speed, travel length (with separate cost functions for diesel/electric trains), types of goods, infrastructure charges, various border crossing time penalties and change of traction type.
The inland waterway freight route choice calculates the cheapest cost routes between possible pairs of Inland Waterway Terminals. The input criteria are the commodity type, the length of the link, and the speed of operations.
5 The main models are numbered from 1 to 7 and will be in split in the following sections
41

The sea freight transport route choice model finds the cheapest cost routes between possible pairs of harbors depending on the type of freight transport and what the harbor can host. The criteria are shipping size and ship type. Calculations are made separately for containers, dry and liquid bulk transport (de Jong et al., 2016).
2 â€“ Chain route choice model and level of service calculation
In this second step, the model determines the combinations (chains) of modes and calculates the costs and time of the optimal chain.
3 â€“ Stochastic Logistic model for choice of chain type
The third step collects the results from the Level of Service and the demand response groupings. It also takes O-D matrices as an input. â€œSince this has not (yet) been calculated for the scenario that a user is evaluating, there is a need for a user-defined base scenario matrix as input. [It also requires a base pivot year matrix to] ensure that the model fits the observed 2010 base matrix if the model is run for the 2010 base yearâ€ (De Jong et al., 2016, p.25).
It then calculates the probability for choosing chain type for freight category. The output is chain type specific O-D matrices (measured in tons or containers).
4.2.2 Demand response
The demand response grouping is a loop. It models how demand for freight transport reacts to change in the level of supply. The Level of Service is the input of the freight demand modeling.
The first step in the demand loop is to calculate the average transport cost and time. Then, the unit adjustment model converts the units of cost and time per ton/container to monetary values.
Next, the trade model intervenes and calculates the change of trade patterns. The trade model takes commodity groups and outputs production-consumption matrices (measured in tons).
42

And finally, the Stochastic Logistic model for choice of chain type is rerun with the calculated Production-Consumption matrices for the scenario year retrieved from the trade model instead of the base scenario matrices.
4.2.3 Route choice and network loading
â€œThe last sequence of models calculates final routes for freight transport and assigns (loads) the flows onto the networks.â€ (De Jong et al., 2016, p.26).
4 â€“ Chain route choice and assignment
The first model is the same as the chain route choice model (2), except that here, the flows are also loaded onto the network. The output is multimodal network flows in tons/containers for the four freight categories. Both single-modal and multimodal O-D matrices can be directly drawn from the output network.
5 â€“ Calculation of vessel flows
This step computes the number of vessels between a given origin-destination pair given the freight flow and size.
The unit of calculation is decimal. For instance, the model may calculate that a given transport is using 0.5 trucks. The reason for this is that the model is a weekday model. So, this basically states that the likelihood for a given truck transport on a given day is 50% (De Jong et al., 2016, p.27).
There are specific calculations of vessel flows for each type of route.
6 â€“ Single model route choice and network loading
Similarly to the first step (1), this model calculates the flows on the network, but both freight flows (tons and containers) and vessels are considered on the network.
43

7 â€“ Impact models
This last model shows the impacts of a given scenario run compared to a base scenario. The impacts are calculated by the means of the following outputs from the freight models:
- Network level: the output is vessel flow and speeds on the transport network level. This is used for impact calculations of safety, energy use, CO2 and other emissions. â€¨
- Unimodal O-D level: the outputs are freight flows (tons or containers) and vessels and level of service (time and cost) for unimodal transports between terminals and end zones (points of production and consumption). â€¨
- Chain O-D level: this calculates O-D Freight flows and level of service per chain type per freight category for an entire chain type for a given O-D pair.
- Production-Consumption freight level: this provides the overall PC matrices and level of service for each of the four freight categories
- Production-Consumption economic level: Overall level of service for each of the four freight categories (De Jong et al., 2016, p.29).
4.2.4 ETISplus Database
ETISplus was a project run by the Institute of Transport and Communications that aimed to design and build a European transport information system. The project was launched in 2009 and was finished in 2012. It was implemented by 18 transport consultants from 11 European countries. It was built on the conclusions of the ETIS project, which was completed in 2005. The project was financed by the European Commission. The TRANS-TOOLS model drew its data from the ETISplus Database.
ETIS stands for European Transport policy Information System. Its goal is to create a database of harmonized European data. It intends to link official statistics to applications in the transport policy theme.
â€œOne of the goals in ETISplus, under this thematic area, was to take all of the data that is publicly available, and use it to generate a best possible estimation at the disaggregate levelâ€ (Szimba et al., 2013, p. 21.1)
44

The main data collection occurred in 2010. However, policy changes can have a drastic importance on the accuracy of the forecasts inducted from this data. These changes are certain, yet their timings are unpredictable. Which is why one of the focuses of the project was to integrate the change in the database updating strategy (Szimba et al., 2013).
4.2.4.1 Methodology: Data Harmonization
Harmonizing data from different countries requires agreements on common definitions. For instance, the definition of the geographic areas within countries must be decided. The mode of transportation and what they encompass has to be defined thoroughly. These definitions might also change over time. Hence, compromises had to be made beforehand in sake of data integrity.
In ETISplus, the data is always matched to a year with its corresponding definition. If a major new collection of data is proceeded, it will come with its matching current definitions. If the user wants to use data from two different periods, the data has to be converted.
The model contains road, rail, waterway, air networks converged in GIS (Geographical Information System) database sets. It gathers information on the shortest paths, road types, transport modes that can be used on the roadsâ€¦ Other linked database sets regroup the data on the terminals and other facilities for modal change (Szimba et al., 2013).
4.2.4.2 Methodology: Freight Matrices
ETISplus created freight matrices for each transport mode. Data availability varies according to the mode; it was retrieved through different sources. Different approaches were taken for each mode.
Road Freight Matrix
Road data was provided by Eurostat and available at the NUTS3 level. The Origin Destination matrix is made in two steps:
45

First, the domestic O-D matrix is calculated for each country, since these each relate to a single data source. â€¨ Then the international O-D matrix is made for all country pairs together (Szimba et al., 2013, p. 19.5).
The advantage for domestic matrices is that the Eurostat provides a thorough NUTS3 to NUTS3 matrix. â€œThe international matrix is more complicated. The incoming and outgoing international transport per zone has to be derived from the total transport and domestic transport per zone. By subtracting the domestic from the total, the international part can be estimated.â€ (Szimba et al., 2013, p. 19.6)
Rail Freight Matrix
Like the road freight matrix, the rail freight matrix was done in stages. The main problem is that no data was available at the NUTS3 level. The data was only available at the NUTS2 or NUTS1 levels, hence data had to be induced. However, the availability of train freight data is relatively low compared to other transport modes. Furthermore, the amount of released per country is inconsistent. For example, Eurostat published no information the domestic traffic of Germany by 2010, despite the country being one of the most important in freight traffic in Europe.
As no data was available for 2010, data from 2005 from Eurostat or national data files was used. Then, information was induced and harmonized to the 2010 ETISplus standards (Szimba et al., 2013).
Waterway Freight Matrix
Data for waterway freight is also quite limited. It is not available at the NUTS3 level, but for the most part, Eurostat was able to provide it at the NUTS2 level. The missing data was retrieved from national sources then converted and harmonized. Once again, the lack of information and consistency for international data was challenging. The waterway freight matrix required the most national sources and the most numerous conversions and induction (Szimba et al., 2013).
46

Air Freight Matrix Air cargo represents a lesser share of freight transport (about 2% of the freight transported globally). The freight was assigned at an aggregate level (per country) which had to be disaggregated at a NUTS3 level. Air cargo focuses on products that have a much shorter life cycle or which have specific characteristics (such as perishable goods). It is ten times more expensive than surface transport. Additional information is present in this matrix given the level of detail. The data was retrieved from WorldNet as a starting point, then induced and harmonized (Szimba et al., 2013).
47

4.3 FAME
The Freight Activity Micro-simulation Estimator (FAME) is a freight activity-based modeling framework. According to Pourabdollahi et al. (2012), it is the first comprehensive nationwide freight demand microsimulation model in the United States. It is composed of five modules (illustrated in Figure 7). It forecasts freight movements at the disaggregate level (firm-to-firm). The model was developed based upon publicly available datasets because â€œstates and planning agencies will more likely adopt models that can be developed using only widely available dataâ€ (Kawamura et al., 2012, p. 26). The data is mostly retrieved from the County Business Patterns dataset. Four categories of data are required for developing FAME:
â€¢ information on business establishments for the first module, â€¢ aggregate freight flows (OD matrix) for the second module, â€¢ detailed information on a sample of individual shipments and supply chains for the third
and fourth tasks, â€¢ and specifications of the transportation networks for the last module.
(Pourabdollahi et al., 2012, p.2) â€¨
48

Figure 7: Framework of the Freight Activity Microsimulation Estimator
(Kawamura et al., 2012)
4.3.1 Firm-type Generation module
This first module identifies all the firms concerned by the study and collects their relevant characteristics. The characteristics include firm type, industry, location and number of employees (Kawamura et al., 2012).
49

In 2009, the County Business Patterns dataset had information on over 239 000 firms. In theory, the FAME model can consider all these companies at once, but the computation costs and inputs required would be considerable. Hence, the model aggregates the firms based on firm types. â€œA firm-type is a collection of firms with similar location, industry type, and establishment sizeâ€ (Kawamura et al., 2012, p. 25). The type of industry is defined by the 2002 North American Industry Classification System (NAICS), which contains around 1200 categories (U.S. Census Bureau, 2002). An important assumption of the FAME model is that firms with similar characteristics have similar behavior in the freight decision-making process (Kawamura et al., 2012).
4.3.2 Supply Chain Replication module
The second module investigates the type and the amount of goods entering and leaving each firm, depending on each firmâ€™s characteristics.
The supply chains are replicated by matching suppliers and buyers of goods. The module is divided in two steps.
The first step determines all the potential suppliers for a given firm type. It lists all the firm types that could provide a commodity to a selected firm-type.
The second step uses probabilities (based on a fuzzy expert system detailed by Kawamura et al. (2012) in their appendices) to determine supplier suitability. These probabilities are namely built upon the commodity researched, the commodities characteristics, the distance between the firms, the characteristics of the firms and the financial situation of the firm (using the number of employees and the growth rate) (Kawamura et al., 2012).
4.3.3 Shipment Forecasting module
This module uses the data previously collected on firms to determine the size of the shipment. It also considers the firmsâ€™ trade habits.
50

This module breaks down annual flows of a given commodity between two firms into single shipments. The output is expressed in terms of weight and distance.
Shipping distance is provided in nine categories (<50 miles, 50-99, 100-249, 250-499, 500749, 750-999, 1000-1499, 1500-2000, >2000), and shipment size is also given in nine categories (<50 lbs., 50-99, 100-499, 500-749, 750-999, 1000-9999, 10000-49999, 5000099999, 100,000<) (Kawamura et al., 2012, p. 40)
However, the next module requires precise weights and distances and wonâ€™t accept categories. Hence conversions and rough estimations can sometimes be performed in case of lack of data (Kawamura et al., 2012).
4.3.4 Logistic Decision module
The mode choice engulfs decisions on shipping mode, haul time, shipping costs, warehousing, etc. The mode split model used in this logistic decision module is the only module that uses not publicly available data. The information was drawn from a survey of businesses (The UIC National Freight Survey) carried out across the USA.
To achieve the goal of developing a model that can only be used only with publicly available data, FAME includes two freight mode choice models that were calibrated based on the UIC National Freight Survey. Depending on the availability of input variables, agencies will be able to select the powerful yet data-hungry explanatory model or the parsimonious model that requires a limited amount of input variables (Kawamura et al., 2012, p. 41).
The variables for each sub-model are listed in Table 8.
51

The Explanatory Model

The Parsimonious Model

Mode (rail and/or road)

Mode (rail and/or road)

Distance

Great circle distance

