(Kawamura et al., 2012).

4.3.5 Network analysis module

Finally, this module finds the impacts of the goods movement on the transportation network.

The general cost of commodity transportation obtained in the network analysis can be fed back into the second modules for multiple iterations, until stabilized commodity flows and costs are achieved.

52

4.4 The Integrated transport system in the Arab Mashreq (ITSAM)
4.4.1 Description of the model
The ITSAM was created in an effort to counteract an export fall in the 1990s. Intraregional trade was very low within the member countries of the United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia (ESCWA). The model simultaneously predicts trip generation, trip distribution, modal split, and trip assignment.
ITSAM contains three components: - ITSAM-NETWORK, an integrated (multimodal) transport network - ITASM-INFOSYS, an associated information system - ITSAM-FRAMEWORK, a methodological framework for issue analysis and policy formulation (Nabil et al., 2004, p.129)
The goal was to create a model to predict freight flow patterns (time and cost) that can describe the behavior of importers and exporters for given countries and commodity sets. The model aims to facilitate intraregional trade and to integrate the countries of ESCWA into the global economy (Nabil et al., 2004).
4.4.2 Development of the model
The Simultaneous Transportation Equilibrium Model (STEM) was introduced in 1982 by Safwat. This model links transportation costs to the trip generation step of the 4-step model (Safwat, 1988). The STEM was then applied to the passenger and freight intercity transport system in Egypt, to the urban transportation network in Texas, to the urban transportation network in Saudi Arabia, etc.
The STEM was then improved to become the International Freight Simultaneous Transportation Equilibrium Model (IFSTEM) in 1999. IFSTEM is a core component of the ITSAM-FRAMEWORK.
53

â€œIFSTEM supports the transportation of several products par several modesâ€ (Nabil et al., 2004, p.130). In this model, a product is a category of commodity or goods.
The network infrastructure represented by IFSTEM gathers cities, border points, rail/road terminals, seaports, airports and intermodal terminals. The model also considers origins, destinations, import and export procedures, transit procedures, and transfer operations. All these are represented by either physical nodes (ports, terminalsâ€¦) or artificial nodes (transit procedures, transfersâ€¦). These artificial nodes are also known as Administrative and Logistical Operations (ALOs).
â€œSince each commodity can be transported by a specific mode or set of modes, depending on commodity characteristics, a network for each commodity type has been created under IFSTEMâ€ (Nabil et al., 2004, p.130). The network is next decomposed in multimodal origindestination matrices. The model then maximizes the exporterâ€™s (or importerâ€™s) utility function.
4.4.3 Assumptions
â€œIFSTEM is constructed in such a way that commodity exporters make decisions about where and how to transport their freight; choices are made regarding destination, mode, transshipment, and routingâ€ (Nabil et al., 2004, p.132).
The delivery cost/price is evaluated with the value of time, the total time, the unit price of a commodity, ALOs costs on the current multimodal path, the tariff cost and the transportation cost.
â€œThe measured utility is a function of the socioeconomic characteristics of the destination (such as consumption levels, commodity deficit, population, and selling prices)â€ (Nabil et al., 2004, p.134).
The model is influenced by how the exporters value time, the Electronic Data Interchange (EDI, level of implementation used to perform operation a for commodity r) and the transport system performance.
54

The demand for the transport of one commodity is independent to any other commodityâ€™s demand. Which is why they are modeled separately, and IFSTEM may therefore be decomposed by commodity type.
Additionally, since capacity issues are generally not a principal concern in regional or international freight transportation planning, it is not necessary to assign multicommodity flows to this international network simultaneously; a simplified separation of freight into commodity groupings is sufficiently relevant. Each commodity or sector becomes a layer, and together, all that is useful for planning. (Nabil et al., 2004, p.135).
The real application of IFSTEM to the ESCWA countriesâ€™ transportation systems requires a calibration process for both demand and supply models to estimate the parameters. The inputs necessary for the ITSAM model are listed in Table 9.
The variables of the ITSAM model The modes to consider (road, rail, sea, air) Commodity types ALOs OD matrices Multimodal Network Generalized cost per unit Number of tons of any commodity Consumption levels Commodity deficit Population Selling prices
Table 9: ITSAM model variables
