Table 10 gathers the factors relevant to compare between the four real-world model analyzed.
Each macro-model takes different variables as input. Some variables are common for all models (mode, commodity type, weight) while others are specific (employment, sales, type of business).
As it was suggested in section 2.6, all these macro-models can solve activity-based problems. They all consider temporal and spatial factors, but also transport actors and logistics8.
As de Jong et al. (2012) mentioned, the inclusion of logistics into these models has been a recurring theme since 2004. The behavior of the shippers, freight forwarders, carrier and drivers are somehow integrated in all four of these models (which was a shortcoming of the classic four-stage model).
Nowadays, the inclusion of logistics is recommended. The last decadeâ€™s trends revealed the need of advanced inventory management to face, inter alia, returns and exchange policies. Anyhow, the consideration of transport costs to the final price of a commodity remains of paramount importance (For instance, the share of transport costs in the final price of bricks is much more important than the share of transport costs in the price of electronics).
Production-Consumption links are also taken into account in all these models. TRANSTOOLS even explicitly utilizes PC matrices. All four macro-models somehow consider production sites and shippers, intermediate processing points and intermediate/end consumer sites.
8 The logistics models typically include all logistics costs and aim to describe the trade-offs between inventory and transport and the routing via â€œintermediate pointsâ€. These points can be transshipment terminals (road terminals, rail terminals, ports, airports) that are used for transfers between modes or different vehicle types of the same mode (allowing for consolidation and deconsolidation), or distribution centres (DC), warehouses where goods are stored, not necessarily labelled for their destination and where goods typically change consignment sizes (de Jong, 2012, p.14).
57

PLANET, TRANS-TOOLS and ITSAM rely on aggregate data for input, which is coherent to the contents of section 3.1. The availability of disaggregate data being one of the major obstacles, most models take aggregate data as input. One of the major preoccupations of the development of these macro-models was to build non-confidential databases, which could only be done with publicly available (and frequently, aggregate) data.
FAME and ITSAM are firm centered, they provide forecasts at the establishment level. Moreover, they take into account actorsâ€™ value of time. FAME only considers firms compatible with the type of goods sent. ITSAM considers more socioeconomic variables than the others (consumption levels, commodity deficit, population, and selling prices, sales).
The PLANET model was the only one to address new technology concerns, such as the arrival of electric vehicles. Alternative future transport modes shouldnâ€™t be neglected (for instance, drones and autonomous robots might be tomorrowâ€™s postmen).
Environment and pollution concerns were only recalled by PLANET and TRANS-TOOLS. These models are quite close. They provide the same types of results, only the inputs vary.
All models are activity-based, but FAMEâ€™s parsimonious model is the only one which doesnâ€™t require shipping time or any other time value to predict demand. The parsimonious model is quite powerful because it only requires a portion of the variables to forecast demand. Although, it is accepted that it might give less accurate results.
It is important to note that the parsimonious and explanatory models may give different results if they are both applied for the same scenario (having all the inputs available).
Referring to the class approached of section 3.4, PLANET, TRANS-TOOLS and ISTAM would be class F because they donâ€™t fully support tours, but have logistic information integrated. The FAME model can however solve tour-based problems (as Kawamura et.al (2011) demonstrated), and is then a part of class G.
58

All models have their pros and cons, the key decision elements as to which one to use are: â€¢ The data available â€¢ The (computing) time available â€¢ The type of commodity to model â€¢ The calibration reference year â€¢ The level of aggregation desired â€¢ The modes to consider â€¢ The outputs desired
These models provide different approaches to forecast demand under different contexts and using different variables. There will forever remain room for improvement in terms of accuracy, performance and relevance of the variable. Further project could always improve transport planning decisions by suggesting more dependent variables, simulating the behavior of all actors, including upcoming trends and technologiesâ€¦ Future models could also consider the jointure of freight and passenger in one transport mode as part of the forecasts (as some ferries transport trucks, vans and passenger vehicles altogether).
59

5 Conclusions and Managerial Implications
This paper began with an explanation of the basic concepts of transport planning. Though it has limitations and was at first applied for passenger planning, the four-stage model was approached as a point of reference. To understand how to predict freight movements, the literature review focused on the first three stages (trip generation, distribution and modal split), on the modelling of these stages and the variables that come into play.
Then, the importance of these models to incorporate time series was highlighted. Activity-based models should be emphasized, and they should express an intuitive link to a macroeconomic metric such as the gross domestic product. Multi-agent systems are able to simulate freight transport generation and incorporate time series.
Next, the classification systems available for freight forecasting models were discussed. The employment was used as an example of a variable that can be used to predict commodity flows.
Section 4 focused on the methodology of macro-models developed across the globe. The aim was to present the methodology used in the making of the macro-models and understand their goals. The scope of these models is different, they were all relevant for different scales and different regions. They were chosen specifically for their diversity. Other studies, such as the paper provided by de Jong et. Al (2004), list macro-models developed in Europe.
Although the literature is still less abundant than for passenger transport planning, the importance of the freight has been illustrated many times.
Economic growth is impacted by transport problems. For instance, the freight supply of an area can be jeopardized by the lack of new transport tracks. â€œA heavily congested or poorly connected system restricts options and limits economic and social developmentâ€ (OrtÃºzar & Willumsen, 2011, p. 3).
Itâ€™s important to notice the link between logistics and economy: monetary transactions are very often accompanied by a commodity flow (and vice versa). The amount of cargo produced and consumed are bound to economic transactions.
60

The freight system is complex, multidimensional, highly heterogeneous and depends on many economic agents. Classification systems are required to approach such a wide concept.
As reminded by OrtÃºzar & Willumsen (2011), models are simplifications of the reality based on assumptions to obtain satisfactory results. They will never provide entirely accurate results, and they will always require some interpretation.
It should also be considered that errors can occur all along the forecasting process. The chosen model could be inadequate, it could neglect a capital factor, the chosen year for calibration could be deficient, â€¦ Let alone uncertainty and inaccuracies have a tendency to grow over time.
The models presented in the paper are primarily tools to aid decision-making. Some allow the calculation of profitability of infrastructure and help to allocate public funding accordingly. They help to test schemes and policies. Transportation policies aim to make sure that the public resources are being shared to sustain the economy and the society. They can also assess impacts on finances, the environment, safety, performance, and on traffic and congestion. Better models provide better forecasts and lead to better decisions.
Industry sectors, international trade networks, public agencies, and other policy makers need accurate information about national freight movements to continue efficiently delivering various goods within and among consumer markets. They need to plan for future freight traffic impacts and evaluate the effectiveness of policies and projects designed to alleviate freight congestion problems.
Finally, the resources allocated to models for analysis should be aligned with the cost of poor decisions. Transport investments and policies are extremely time-consuming, requiring models to predict scenarios that do not currently exist. Most freight forecasting models are expensive, but they can prevent much higher costs that could occur in the case of unforeseen circumstances (such as infrastructure costs).
61

