7 Appendices
Appendix 1
The next flow chart summarizes the procedure to quantify the FSA according to HolguÃ­n-Veras, J. et al. The scenarios are the ones explained above in Table 5.
67

(HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016) 68

The models suggested separated the generation of demand from the generation of the FSA traffic, which allows them to be more flexible, realistic and implementable to a wider range of situations.
Even though the demand generation is the expression of economic fluctuations, the generation of vehicle trips depends on logistics and distribution. Depending on their locations, two identical establishments could generate different numbers of trips (if the establishment is close to other facilities, suppliers could group deliveries and have them more frequent, for instance).
This decomposition requires the usual measurements of demand forecasts (deliveries/day, shipments out/day, service calls/day, or pounds/day) to be transformed into vehicle trips. Appendix 2 summarizes the conversion of these measurements (HolguÃ­n-Veras et al., 2016).
HolguÃ­n-Veras, J. et al (2016) have displayed five limits of the models they have gathered: â€¢ All their data comes from the United States, hence the relevance to any substantially different sector might result in inaccuracies. â€¢ Only basic variables common to all databases were used in order to ensure continuity between models. â€¢ They were not able to gather data on Service Trip Production and Freight Attraction â€¢ Most of the data collected concerns small businesses. Data from larger establishments (over 100 employees) is hard to obtain. â€¢ The assumption of linking employment to the demand forecasts hinders the explanatory power
69

